Q3.8: It could be helpful to have more online asynchronous classes for the Graduate Program 3 that are not so accelerated. Most classes, if not all, that I've seen are 14 weeks of material condensed into 7 weeks which makes it very challenging to keep up with if, like I did, people have demanding full time jobs. Also there is a lot of pressure to post discussion board posts and responses and I learned nothing or very little from these, given the relatively high amount of time I spent on them, and then I just gave up. I suppose you could see these as two different suggestions but they sort of go hand-in-hand, in my opinion. Overall though I love the program and have found an extremely high degree of support from the advisors and flexibility from the professors which makes everything worth it.

Q3.8:
Introduce more interdisciplinary project-based courses that connect classroom learning with real-world challenges.
For example, students could collaborate across programs, like management, cybersecurity, and psychology, to solve practical issues faced by local organizations or community partners. This hands-on, cross-disciplinary approach would deepen academic engagement, build teamwork and problem-solving skills, and provide Augustin College School students with tangible experience they can carry into their careers.
Q4.7: One initiative I would recommend to enhance the student experience at Augustin College is the creation of a dedicated student lounge and community space specifically for Augustin College students. Many adult learners or part-time students often come to campus outside traditional hours and may not feel as connected to campus life. A welcoming space with flexible hours, access to study areas, coffee/tea, and occasional programming or networking events would foster a stronger sense of belonging, community, and support among students.
Q5.3: Augustin College should incorporate a stronger emphasis on career development and post-graduation support tailored to non-traditional and mid-career students. This could include partnerships with industry mentors, targeted job placement services, and short-term credential programs or certifications that align with market trends. By integrating career-focused resources into its mission, Augustin College can empower students not just academically, but professionally, ensuring they're equipped to thrive in a rapidly changing workforce.

Q3.8: I think more in-person classes, i.e. a more varied selection of available in-person classes to take each semester, would be beneficial. I think it's great to offer fully remote/asynchronous classes in order to guarantee wider accessibility (and also obviously more marketable). However, I found that, being local to Veritus Imperial University and wanting to leverage as many in-person experiences as possible (as I believe, and I think confirmed through this semester, that those are more valuable academically and professionally) I had an extremely limited selection of courses that I could take in a given semester and count toward my certificate requirements. The current model seems to be remote-first, hybrid-second; I would have preferred the other way around.
Q4.7: I do think that more evening/weekend events and volunteer opportunities for Augustin College students who work full-time but still want to build community would be beneficial.
Q5.3: My own perception (perhaps an assumption) about Augustin College is that it is primarily designed for adult and nontraditional students who may work full-time or have other personal commitments. I believe this is an important (mission-wise) and marketable (financially) niche to appeal to. However, my experience so far at Augustin College has been primarily with full-time students who had either immediately or recently completed their undergraduate degree, often from Veritus Imperial University. That's fine - my classmates have all been smart and engaged - but the class conversations often lack the depth that I was expecting from a college designed for students with diverse professional and personal experiences. It also leaves me somewhat confused as to what the mission and target audience of Augustin College is supposed to be. Again, the classes are great, and the classmates are great, but I do not feel like I am really experiencing (or maybe I misunderstand it) an academic program designed for nontraditional students / professionals.

Q3.8:
To better support graduate students who are balancing coursework with professional and personal responsibilities, I recommend that all asynchronous courses adopt a consistent structure and schedule for assignments and deadlines.

Proposed Structure:

Assignment Release: Every Monday

Assignment Due Date: The following Monday

Time Zone: Clearly stated and consistent (e.g., 11:59 PM EST)

Rationale:

Predictability: A uniform weekly schedule helps students plan their work and personal time more effectively.

Reduced Cognitive Load: Eliminates the need to manage multiple inconsistent course calendars.

Improved Time Management: Encourages students to establish a regular weekly routine, which can lead to better performance and reduced stress.

Q1.18: Hybrid (combination of in-person and online courses)
Q3.8:
I am now in my third semester in the Augustin College, and I have noticed three glaring shortfalls: turnaround from professors grading assignments, forced group work, and lack of continuity between when assignments are actually due and when they show up as due on Blackboard. 

- Pre or Post-work assignments should not be due until the previous week's assignment has been graded. Submitting assignments without receiving feedback from a previous assignment leaves the student lost. and asking if they are on the right track. 

- Group work causes more harm than good. I thought this program would have more part-time students and almost no full-time students. I have found that many of my classes lack part-time students, creating a massive divide of when people are available. I think group work is important, but it should not be emphasized as much as it is. The most difficult part of the assignment is generally finding time to meet and it takes away from the actual assignment. 

- If Blackboard is going to be used, then the assignment due dates should match what is shown in the application. I am now in my third class, where a teacher posts a due date for an assignment that does not match the application. If a teacher is going to ask for discussion due one day but replies are due another, then it should show as two different assignments in the application with two different due dates.
